title: Services Trainer
description: Instructor and Curriculum Development Specialist for the Drilling Platform (subsea). Responsible for developing course material or projects with advanced to extreme complexity; define educational objectives and instructional methodologies; and resolve issues through immediate action and short/long-term planning. • Maintain an in-depth knowledge of applicable regulatory requirements • Work with Regional Leaders to establish training requirements • Provide training in GE Product Lines to Field Service Engineers • Liaise with regional leaders and cutomers to determine training requirements • Develop technical training related to the operation and maintenance of new products • Define development and delivery requirements for technical training programs • Design and create training materials to support instructor led training in a classroom or lab environment • Create knowledge and skill based assessments of learners • Evaluate training courses and identify improvement opportunities • Implement / modify programs and procedures to ensure company compliance • Maintain an in-depth knowledge of applicable regulatory requirements • Develop and work with site teams focused on program development, implementation and improvement Current Role(s): - Dual Gradient Drilling (GE MaxLift) Senior Technical Competency and Curriculum Developer, Trainer & Advisor - Hydril MultiPlex Pod Advanced Hydraulics Technical Curriculum Developer & Trainer - Hydril Blow Out Preventers Hydraulic Technical Curriculum Developer & Trainer - Hydril Control Systems (MultiPlex) Technical Electrical Curriculum Developer & Advisor - GE SeaOnyx Control Systems Technical Software Curriculum Developer & Trainer

title: Senior Operations Supervisor
description: Served as the Senior Operations Supervisor for the United States Army Military Intelligence Basic Officers Leadership Course; responsible for all administrative, finance, medical and training actions for a 300-person organization; collaborates and coordinates for world-wide personnel assignments; schedules and conducts executive level presentations regarding policies, procedures, and processes; provides subject matter expertise to ensure training is conducted within regulatory guidance and standards. Established the unit Emergency Operations Center during the 2011 Arizona Monument Fire ensuring the accountability, health, safety and welfare of more than 600 personnel and their families during prescribed evacuations; effectively communicated subsequent process improvements and implemented immediate changes as necessary. Served as a volunteer for the Arizona Rangers (Badge #605), Tombstone Patrol Unit, and recognized by the Sierra Vista Police Department as the Volunteer of the Year for 2011; inspired others to contribute more than 10,000 hours of volunteer community service.

title: Senior Instructor/Writer (MIBOLC)
description: Developed and implemented the US Army Military Intelligence Basic Officers Leadership Course Marksmanship Training Program; responsible for establishing training goals, developing curriculum, and measuring accomplishments against learning objectives. Served as a senior team leader for 14 Competence Assessors (CA) to define roles, missions and resources; assessed the organizational structure and effectiveness within a dynamic and unique environment. Provided leadership and expertise to more than 40 instructors during annual senior-level long-term planning events involving the creation of technical training programs. Collaborated with the Department of the Army Finance Command to develop and implement a series of improvement plans for identifying poor quality assurance/quality control issues with processing temporary duty travel claims for initial entry personnel attending Department of the Army Schools.

title: Rear Detachment First Sergeant
description: Subject matter expert in identifying resources and utilizing unique leadership techniques that positively inﬂuences people by providing purpose, direction, and motivation while operating to accomplish the mission and improve the organization. Served as a senior intelligence analyst supervising the collection, management, and dissemination of data gathered by Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAV) and other aerial platforms operating on the borders of Iraq, Syria, Jordan, and Iran. Drafted and built a series of five intelligence-oriented databases for a multi-national coalition to store, assess, analyze and predict significant activities. Responsible for more than $100,000 of Rapid Force Initiative equipment being sent forward to deployed Soldiers.

title: Instructor/Writer (BOLC II)
description: Designed and implemented courseware incorporating US Army tactics, Critical Thinking, Intelligence Preparation of the Battlefield (IPB), Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR), Mission Analysis, the Military Decision Making Process (MDMP) to support Analysis and Battle Tracking scenarios in a conventional, symmetrical conflict. Selected to lead the Direct Commissioned Officers Course Program of Instruction annual review; successfully revised and authored 30 new Training Support Packages. Identified and designed 54 student training plans in order to develop training capabilities, competencies, and safety control measures within the prescribed Program of Instruction for initial military training. Trained, supervised, and mentored more than 29 United States Army Soldier-Instructors in a combat environment on critical skills involving event monitoring, event correlations, and event management to validate proposed levels of escalation and responses.

title: Senior Intelligence Sergeant
description: Served as the Senior All-Source Intelligence Sergeant, Database Management Supervisor, and Targeting Supervisor for the Coalition Analysis and Control Element (CACE) for the Combined Joint Task Force Seven (CJTF-7) during Operation Iraqi Freedom. Responsible for the creation and management of five intelligence databases for the CJTF-7 C2 used to track over 50,000 indigenous personnel in the Iraqi Area of Operations. Responsible for the maintenance, servicing, distribution and training on all weapons and communications systems for 122 Soldiers. Responsible for the training, supervision and welfare of 22 personnel and equipment valued at more than $2.5M. Developed and produced analytical products and conducted briefings for the V Corps and Multi National Forces-Iraq (MNF-I) Commanding Generals.
